# Fix npm installation method detection via node_modules path check

**Issue**: CLI-Y1 — `UpgradeError: Could not detect installation method` on Windows when installed via npm.

## Root Cause

When installed via npm (or any JS package manager), `detectInstallationMethod()` in `src/lib/upgrade.ts` relies on spawning `npm list -g sentry`, `pnpm list -g`, etc. to detect the install method. On Windows (especially with NVM-managed Node.js), these spawns fail with ENOENT because `.cmd` executables aren't resolved without `shell: true`. The CLI returns `"unknown"` despite running from a `node_modules` directory — a very strong signal it was installed by a package manager.

## Fix

Add a fast, authoritative path-based check `detectPackageManagerFromPath()` that examines `process.argv[1]` for a `node_modules` segment. This mirrors the existing Homebrew `/Cellar/` check — cheap, reliable, and overrides stale DB state.

### Files to modify

1. **`src/lib/upgrade.ts`** — Add detection function + wire it into the cascade
2. **`test/lib/upgrade.test.ts`** — Add test cases for path-based detection

### Changes in `src/lib/upgrade.ts`

#### 1. Add `detectPackageManagerFromPath()` (after `isHomebrewInstall()`, ~line 201)

```typescript
function detectPackageManagerFromPath(): PackageManager | null {
  const scriptPath = process.argv[1];
  if (!scriptPath) return null;

  const segments = scriptPath.split(/[\\/]/);  // cross-platform
  if (!segments.includes("node_modules")) return null;

  if (segments.includes(".pnpm")) return "pnpm";
  return "npm";  // default for npm/yarn/bun global layouts
}
```

Key design decisions:
- Uses `process.argv[1]` — Node.js always sets this to the script path; Bun compiled binaries set it to the first CLI arg (never contains `node_modules`)
- Splits on both `/` and `\` for Windows compatibility
- Detects pnpm via its distinctive `.pnpm` directory; defaults to `"npm"` for other layouts
- Windows 8.3 short paths (e.g., `CONFIG~1`) don't affect `node_modules` segment detection

#### 2. Wire into `detectInstallationMethod()` — after Homebrew, before DB lookup

```typescript
export async function detectInstallationMethod(): Promise<InstallationMethod> {
  if (isHomebrewInstall()) return "brew";

  // NEW: Check if running from node_modules (authoritative, like Homebrew)
  const pmFromPath = detectPackageManagerFromPath();
  if (pmFromPath) {
    setInstallInfo({ method: pmFromPath, path: process.argv[1] ?? "", version: CLI_VERSION });
    return pmFromPath;
  }

  const stored = getInstallInfo();
  if (stored?.method) return stored.method;

  const legacyMethod = await detectLegacyInstallationMethod();
  // ... (rest unchanged)
}
```

Placing it before the DB lookup ensures:
- Stale DB info (e.g., user previously had curl, switched to npm) is overridden
- The result is persisted so subsequent runs hit the DB fast path

### Test cases in `test/lib/upgrade.test.ts`

New describe blocks:

**`detectInstallationMethod — node_modules path detection`**
- Standard npm path (Unix): `/usr/local/lib/node_modules/sentry/dist/bin.cjs` → `"npm"`
- pnpm path: `.../node_modules/.pnpm/sentry@0.27.0/node_modules/sentry/dist/bin.cjs` → `"pnpm"`
- Windows backslash path: `C:\Users\...\node_modules\sentry\dist\bin.cjs` → `"npm"`
- Windows 8.3 short path (from real bug report): `C:\Users\Minhyung\CONFIG~1\herd\bin\nvm\v24.2.0\node_modules\sentry\dist\index.cjs` → `"npm"`
- No `argv[1]` → falls through (no detection)
- Bun compiled binary `argv[1]` = `"issue"` → falls through
- Dev mode path without `node_modules` → falls through
- Overrides stale curl in DB → returns `"npm"`, not `"curl"`
- Persists to DB after detection

Test setup: save/restore `process.argv` and `process.execPath` in beforeEach/afterEach. Set `execPath` to a non-Homebrew, non-curl path (e.g., `/usr/bin/node`) so detection falls through to the path check.

## What this does NOT fix

The Windows spawn ENOENT issue for `executeUpgradePackageManager()` is a separate problem — even after detecting "npm", the upgrade command will try `npm install -g sentry@version` which may also ENOENT on Windows without `shell: true`. That's a separate issue for a follow-up PR.

